{"id":"comp-gas/9612001","submitter":"Xiaowen Shan","authors":"Xiaowen Shan, (Complex Systems Group, Los Alamos National Lab)","title":"Simulation of Rayleigh-B\\'enard convection using lattice Boltzmann\n  method","comments":"20 pages, REVTEX","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.55.2780","report-no":null,"categories":"comp-gas nlin.CG","license":null,"abstract":"  Rayleigh-B\\'enard convection is numerically simulated in two- and\nthree-dimensions using a recently developed two-component lattice Boltzmann\nequation (LBE) method. The density field of the second component, which evolves\naccording to the advection-diffusion equation of a passive-scalar, is used to\nsimulate the temperature field. A body force proportional to the temperature is\napplied, and the system satisfies the Boussinesq equation except for a slight\ncompressibility. A no-slip, isothermal boundary condition is imposed in the\nvertical direction, and periodic boundary conditions are used in horizontal\ndirections. The critical Rayleigh number for the onset of the Rayleigh-B\\'enard\nconvection agrees with the theoretical prediction. As the Rayleigh number is\nincreased higher, the steady two-dimensional convection rolls become unstable.\nThe wavy instability and aperiodic motion observed, as well as the Nusselt\nnumber as a function of the Rayleigh number, are in good agreement with\nexperimental observations and theoretical predictions. The LBE model is found\nto be efficient, accurate, and numerically stable for the simulation of fluid\nflows with heat and mass transfer.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 9 Dec 1996 23:05:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-08-31"}
